<!--     $f(x)=\frac{x-a}{x^2-a^2}$. -->
<!--   \item Does your solution of part (a) still work when $a=0$? -->
<!--   \end{enumerate} -->
<!-- \end{embeddedproblem} -->

<problem xml:id="problem:FoliumOfDescartes2">
<introduction>
<p>
  <!-- <!-\- \label{problem:FoliumOfDescartes2} -\-> -->
  Recall that in Problem~\#\ref{problem:FoliumOfDescartes1} in
  Section~\ref{subsec:Derivative}  looked at the Folium of
  Descartes from Newton's dynamic point of view. 
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2in,width=2in]{../Figures/FoliumOfDescartes}}
  
  In that problem you showed that the fluents, $x(t) =
  \frac{3t}{1+t^3}$ and $y(t)=\frac{3t^2}{1+t^3}$ satisfy the equation
  of the Folium:
  $$
  x^3+y^3=3xy
  $$
  and that $t=0$ is the only value of $t$ where $\left(x(t), y(t)
  \right)=(0,0)$. How then, can it be that the Folium crosses itself
  at the origin?
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 In Problem~\#\ref{problem:FoliumOfDescartes1} you determined that
    $y\ge0$ when $t\gt-1$. Determine the values of $t$ for which  $x\ge0$
    and the which  $x\lt0$.
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Show that
    $\limit{t}{\pm\infty}{x(t)}=\limit{t}{\pm\infty}{y(t)}=0.$
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Compute $\dfdx{y}{x} = \frac{\dot{y}}{\dot{x}}$  in
    terms of $t$ and compute $\limit{t}{\pm\infty}{\frac{\dot{y}}{\dot{x}}}$.  Is this consistent with what you
    see on  the graph?
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Show that for $t\neq0$, $t=\frac{y}{x}$ so that
    geometrically, $t$ represents the slope of the line joining
    the origin to the point $(x,y)$ on the graph of the Folium.
    Is this consistent with what you obtained in part a? 
    Explain.
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Compute each of the following:
    
<ol>
    <li>
<p>
 $\rtlimit{t}{-1}{x(t)}$
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 $\ltlimit{t}{-1}{x(t)}$
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 $\rtlimit{t}{-1}{y(t)}$%{t\gt -1}$
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 $\ltlimit{t}{-1}{y(t)}$%{t\gt -1}$
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
